window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>1","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : ORGANIZATION OF LIFE","question":"At what level of organisation is Amoeba?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Tissue","B":"Organ","C":"Cellular","D":"System"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Amoeba is a single-celled organism. It is not a tissue, organ, or system, which are all composed of multiple cells. Therefore, the level of organization of Amoeba is cellular.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>2","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : ORGANIZATION OF LIFE","question":"Which of these could be regarded as an advantage of complexity in higher organisms?","images":[],"options":{"A":"there is no cellular differentiation","B":"Cellular differentiation leads to loss of independence of the cells","C":"Cellular differentiation occurs in few cells only","D":"Cellular differentiation leads to internal structural specialization"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Complexity in higher organisms is often associated with cellular differentiation, which leads to internal structural specialization. This means that different cells have different roles, allowing the organism to perform a variety of functions efficiently. For example, in humans, we have nerve cells for transmitting signals, red blood cells for carrying oxygen, and so on. This specialization is an advantage of complexity in higher organisms.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>3","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : FORMS IN WHICH LIVING CELLS EXIST","question":"Which of the following organisms is one-celled and free-living?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Volvox","B":"Spirogyra","C":"Rhizopus","D":"Chlamydomonas"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Chlamydomonas is a one-celled and free-living organism. It is a type of green algae that is found in stagnant water and on damp soil. Unlike Volvox, Spirogyra, and Rhizopus, which are multicellular, Chlamydomonas is unicellular. It is capable of photosynthesis, and it can move using its two flagella. It is considered free-living because it does not rely on a host or other organism for survival.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>4","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"One of the differences between plant and animal cells is that in plants","images":[],"options":{"A":"cells have less distinct outline, but animal cells have distinct outline","B":"cell wall is made of cellulose, but animal cell wall is made of chitin","C":"large vacuoles are absent, but present in animals","D":"carbohydrates are stored as starch, but as glycogen in animals."},"answer":"D","explanation":"One of the differences between plant and animal cells is that plant cells store carbohydrates as starch, while animal cells store them as glycogen. This is because starch is the primary form of carbohydrate storage in plants, while glycogen serves the same purpose in animals. The other options are incorrect because plant cells have a distinct outline due to the presence of a cell wall, the cell wall in plants is made of cellulose while animal cells do not have a cell wall, and large vacuoles are present in plant cells but are smaller or absent in animal cells.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>5","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"Carbondioxide enters the stomata during photosynthesis through the process known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"osmosis","B":"active transport","C":"diffusion","D":"inhalation"},"answer":"C","explanation":"During photosynthesis, carbon dioxide enters the stomata through the process known as diffusion. Diffusion is the movement of molecules from an area of higher concentration to an area of lower concentration. In this case, the concentration of carbon dioxide is usually higher in the atmosphere than inside the leaf, so it diffuses into the stomata.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>6","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"Which of the following groups carry out similar functions in living things?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Vertebral column, chitin, and guard cells","B":"Sclerenchyma, cartilage and chitin","C":"Tendon, chitin and neurone","D":"Collenchyma, Intercellular spaces and blood vessels"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Sclerenchyma is a type of plant tissue that provides support and protection, while cartilage is a type of connective tissue in animals that provides cushioning and support. Chitin,  provides support and protection to arthropods and some fungi. Sclerenchyma, cartilage, and chitin all carry out similar functions of providing support and protection.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>7","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"Which of the following statements is correct?","images":[],"options":{"A":"biceps muscles has its origin on the head of the humerus","B":"biceps muscle is inserted at the ulna","C":"triceps muscle originated at the scapula and head of the humerus","D":"ulna is pulled up when the biceps is relaxed"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The triceps brachii muscle has three heads: the long head originating from the scapula and the lateral and medial heads originating from the posterior surface of the humerus. The biceps brachii does not insert into the ulna; it inserts into the radial tuberosity of the radius. The triceps brachii originates from the scapula and the humerus.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>8","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"Which of the following pairs of tissues is responsible for strengthening the plant?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Phloem and Epidermis","B":"Parenchyma and Cambium","C":"Collenchyma and Sclerenchyma","D":"Collenchyma and Cambium"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Collenchyma provides extra mechanical and structural support, particularly in regions of new growth. Sclerenchyma provides the main structural support to a plant.  Collenchyma: Provides flexible support to growing regions of the plant, such as stems and leaves.  Sclerenchyma: Provides rigid support to mature parts of the plant, with thick, lignified cell walls that contribute significantly to the plant's structural integrity.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>9","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"Which of the following is not a tissue found in plants?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Epidermis","B":"Phloem","C":"Xylem","D":"Dermis"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In the context of plant biology, the dermis is not a tissue found in plants. The dermis is a layer of skin found in animals, not plants. On the other hand, Epidermis, Phloem, and Xylem are all types of tissues found in plants. The Epidermis is the outermost layer of cells covering the plant, Phloem is the vascular tissue in plants which conducts sugars and other metabolic products downwards from the leaves, and Xylem is the vascular tissue in plants that conducts water and dissolved nutrients upwards from the root and also helps to form the woody element in the stem.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>10","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TRANSPORT SYSTEM","question":"Higher organisms use a transport system and not diffusion only to distribute nutrients because","images":[],"options":{"A":"the ratio of their surface area to volume is small","B":"metabolic waste products diffuse to the surface of the organisms","C":"the rate at which nutrients and other substances diffuse increases","D":"substances to be transported move shorter distances to reach the numerous cells"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Higher organisms use a transport system and not diffusion only to distribute nutrients because the ratio of their surface area to volume is small. This means that the surface area is not large enough to allow sufficient nutrients to diffuse into the organism to meet its needs. Therefore, a transport system is needed to distribute nutrients effectively. Diffusion is a process where molecules move from an area of high concentration to an area of low concentration. In larger organisms, this process alone is not efficient enough to distribute nutrients to all cells, hence the need for a transport system.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>11","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : FOOD WEBS AND TROPHIC LEVELS","question":"In complex food relationships in a community, the primary, secondary and tertiary consumers are referred to as","images":[],"options":{"A":"symbionts","B":"omnivores","C":"heterotrophs","D":"autotrophs"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In a food chain, the primary, secondary, and tertiary consumers are referred to as heterotrophs. Heterotrophs are organisms that cannot produce their own food and rely on other organisms for their nutrition. They consume other organisms to get the energy and nutrients they need to live. This includes all animals, some types of fungi, and some bacteria. The options 'symbionts', 'omnivores', and 'autotrophs' are incorrect because symbionts are organisms that live in close association with another organism, omnivores are animals that eat both plants and animals, and autotrophs are organisms that can produce their own food from inorganic substances.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>12","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : THE CELL AND ITS ENVIRONMENT","question":"The cell membrane of a cell is said to be semi-permeable because","images":[],"options":{"A":"it allows only large molecular substances to pass through it into the cell","B":"it is actively involved in energy production in the cell","C":"it actively allows all substances to pass through it by diffusion","D":"it is actively selective in allowing substances pass through it"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The cell membrane is semi-permeable because it is selectively permeable, meaning it allows certain substances to pass through it while blocking others. This is achieved through various mechanisms such as passive transport (diffusion and osmosis), active transport, and vesicular transport. The cell membrane controls the movement of substances in and out of the cell, maintaining the cell's internal balance. Therefore, option 4 is correct as it states that the cell membrane is actively selective in allowing substances to pass through it.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>13","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"Use the diagram below to answer the question       The function of the part labelled I is","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"controlling water loss","B":"trapping solar energy","C":"absorbing water","D":"storing sugar"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The part labeled \"I\" is identified as a chloroplast based on its shape and location within the plant cell. Chloroplasts are organelles responsible for photosynthesis, capturing solar energy and converting it into chemical energy. This accurately fits the description of trapping solar energy","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>14","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"Use the diagram below to answer the question     The part labelled ll is the","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"stoma","B":"palisade cell","C":"spongy cell","D":"guard cell"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Guard cells surround an opening called the stoma. The stoma is the actual pore that allows for gas exchange. Therefore, the part labeled \"II,\" which appears to be an opening flanked by two specialized cells, is the stoma.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>15","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"Use the diagram below to answer the question     The structure that will be stained blue-black by iodine is labelled","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"I","B":"II","C":"III","D":"IV"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Iodine stains starch blue-black. The part labeled \"I\" appears to be chloroplasts, which are sites of starch storage in leaf cells. Therefore, the structure labeled \"I\" will be stained blue-black by iodine due to the presence of starch.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>16","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : RESPIRATORY SYSTEM","question":"In the anaerobic stage of respiration, the net ATP molecules produced per glucose molecule","images":[],"options":{"A":"one","B":"two","C":"three","D":"four"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In the anaerobic stage of respiration, also known as glycolysis, one glucose molecule is broken down into two molecules of pyruvate. This process results in the net production of two ATP molecules. Therefore, the correct answer is 'two'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>17","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS","question":"Reabsorption of the metabolic products along the kidney tubules is made possible by the","images":[],"options":{"A":"closeness of the intestine to the kidney","B":"convoluted nature of the tubules","C":"presence of convoluted tubules in the medulla","D":"presence of network of capillaries around the convoluted tubules"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Presence of network of capillaries around the convoluted tubules: The peritubular capillaries wrap around the proximal and distal convoluted tubules, providing a large surface area for the exchange of substances. This network is essential for reabsorbing water, glucose, amino acids, and ions from the filtrate back into the blood, ensuring that valuable substances are not lost in urine. The close proximity of these capillaries to the tubules facilitates efficient transfer of metabolic products, making reabsorption possible.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>18","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : HORMONAL COORDINATION","question":"Hormones are transported around the mammalian body by","images":[],"options":{"A":"water","B":"nerves","C":"blood","D":"osmosis"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Hormones are transported around the mammalian body by the circulatory system, specifically through the blood. Hormones are chemical messengers that are secreted directly into the blood, which carries them to organs and tissues of the body to exert their functions. They are not transported by water, nerves or osmosis. Therefore, the correct answer is 'blood'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>19","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : HORMONAL COORDINATION","question":"Which of the following is not a function of insulin?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Accelerates the rate at which glucose is converted to glycogen","B":"Promotes the uptake of glucose by tissues","C":"Regulates the amount of glucose in the blood","D":"Stimulates muscles to oxidize glucose."},"answer":"D","explanation":"Insulin is a hormone produced by the pancreas that regulates the amount of glucose in the blood. It promotes the uptake of glucose by tissues and accelerates the rate at which glucose is converted to glycogen for storage. However, insulin does not directly stimulate muscles to oxidize glucose. The oxidation of glucose in muscles is a process that occurs during cellular respiration to produce energy, and while insulin can influence this process indirectly by controlling the amount of glucose available, it does not directly stimulate it.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>20","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : NERVOUS COORDINATION","question":"Which of the following is the correct route of transmission of impulses along a reflex arc?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Receptor \u2192 sensory neurone \u2192 synapse \u2192 intermediate neurone \u2192 synapse \u2192 motor neurone \u2192 effector","B":"Receptor \u2192 motor neutron e synapse \u2192 intermediate neurone \u2192 synapse \u2192 sensory neurone effector","C":"Receptor \u2192 synapse \u2192 sensory neurone \u2192 intermediate neurone \u2192 synapse \u2192 effector \u2192 motor neurone","D":"Effector \u2192 motor neurone \u2192 synapse \u2192 sensory neurone \u2192 synapse \u2192 intermediate neurone \u2192 receptor"},"answer":"A","explanation":"A reflex arc is a neural pathway that controls a reflex action. In a reflex arc, the stimulus (received by the receptor) is directly relayed into the sensory neuron, which then sends the information to the intermediate neuron in the spinal cord. This intermediate neuron then sends the signal through a synapse to the motor neuron, which finally carries the signal to the effector (muscle or gland) to respond to the stimulus.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>21","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : SENSE ORGANS","question":"Which of the following statements is false?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Human sense of smell is easily fatigued","B":"The skin can perceive the sensations of touch, pain, pressure and temperature","C":"Taste buds and olfactory cells are active when wet as well as when dry","D":"Sensory nerve endings receive stimuli and send to the central nervous system"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Taste buds and olfactory cells are only active when wet. They require a moist environment to function properly. Taste buds are specialized sensory cells located on the tongue that allow us to perceive different tastes (sweet, sour, bitter, salty, and umami). Olfactory cells, located in the nasal cavity, allow us to perceive smells. Both of these types of cells require a moist environment to dissolve the chemicals they detect, which is why our sense of taste and smell can be impaired when our mouth or nose is dry.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>22","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : SENSE ORGANS","question":"The following are directly involved in transmission of sound waves to the brain except","images":[],"options":{"A":"eardrum","B":"auditory meatus","C":"auditory ossicles","D":"eustachian tube"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Sound waves are transmitted to the brain through a series of structures in the ear. The process begins when sound waves enter the ear through the auditory meatus (ear canal) and cause the eardrum to vibrate. These vibrations are then transferred to the auditory ossicles (tiny bones in the middle ear), which amplify the sound and send it to the inner ear. From there, the sound is converted into electrical signals that are transmitted to the brain. The eustachian tube, however, is not directly involved in the transmission of sound waves to the brain. Its primary function is to equalize pressure between the middle ear and the atmosphere, which is important for the proper functioning of the eardrum and ossicles, but it does not directly transmit sound.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>23","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"The term syncarpous is used to describe a flower when the carpels are","images":[],"options":{"A":"many and fused","B":"two only","C":"two and separate","D":"many and free"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The term syncarpous is used to describe a flower when the carpels are many and fused. Syncarpous: Syncarpous is a condition in which the carpels of the gynoecium are united in a compound ovary. Blooms having syncarpous ovaries include tomato and mustard flowers. It can be either unilocular or multilocular in nature but only one ovary is present. It matures into one fruit with one or more seeds.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>24","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"Which of the following structures are characteristics of insect pollinated flowers?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Dull coloured flowers with no nectar","B":"Very light numerous and pendulous stamen","C":"Brightly coloured petals, scent nectar","D":"Flowers are usually small and inconspicuous"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Insect pollinated flowers, also known as entomophilous flowers, are usually brightly colored and have a strong scent to attract insects. They also produce nectar which serves as a food source for the insects. The insects, while feeding on the nectar, pick up pollen from the flower and transfer it to other flowers, thereby aiding in pollination. Therefore, the option 'Brightly coloured petals, scent nectar' is correct.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>25","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGY OF POPULATION : FACTORS THAT AFFECT POPULATION","question":"Which of the following statements is not correct?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Shortage of food may be caused by pestilence, rinderpest and neglect of farming","B":"Shortage of food may lead to competition, emigration, death and decline in the rate of reproduction","C":"Over-crowding may lead to scarcity of food","D":"Territorial defence encourages food scarcity in a habitat"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Territorial defense does not encourage food scarcity in a habitat. Instead, it is a behavior exhibited by animals to protect their territory, or the area which they inhabit and where they find their food, from intruders. This behavior ensures that the resources within their territory, including food, are not depleted by others. Therefore, territorial defense is a strategy to prevent food scarcity, not to encourage it.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>26","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : POPULATION STUDIES BY SAMPLING","question":"Which of the following is an advantage of dispersal of fruits and seeds? It allows","images":[],"options":{"A":"fair distribution of source of food for animals","B":"growth in close association with parent plant","C":"even distribution of plants and reduction of intraspecific competition","D":"keen competition for food"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The dispersal of fruits and seeds allows for the even distribution of plants and reduction of intraspecific competition. Dispersal is a mechanism that plants use to colonize new areas, which can be far from the parent plant. This reduces intraspecific competition, which is competition among members of the same species for the same resources. By spreading out, plants can access resources without having to compete with their siblings. Dispersal does not necessarily ensure a fair distribution of food for animals, it does not promote growth in close association with the parent plant, and it does not lead to keen competition for food.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>27","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"The series of changes that occur in a seed by which the embryo develops into a seedling is known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"fertilization","B":"gametogenesis","C":"pollination","D":"germination"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The series of changes that occur in a seed by which the embryo develops into a seedling is known as germination. Germination is the process by which an organism grows from a seed or similar structure. The most common example of germination is the sprouting of a seedling from a seed of an angiosperm or gymnosperm. In contrast, fertilization is the fusion of gametes to initiate the development of a new individual organism. Gametogenesis is a biological process by which diploid or haploid precursor cells undergo cell division and differentiation to form mature haploid gametes. Pollination is the transfer of pollen from a male part of a plant to a female part of a plant, later enabling fertilisation and the production of seeds, most often by an animal or by wind.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>28","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGICAL MANAGEMENT : BIOLOGICAL ASSOCIATIONS","question":"Which of the following organisms has a symbiotic relationship with green algae?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Amoeba","B":"Paramecium","C":"Hydra","D":"Euglena"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Hydra has a symbiotic relationship with green algae. In this relationship, the green algae live in the cells of the hydra and perform photosynthesis, providing the hydra with nutrients. In return, the hydra provides the algae with protection and access to light. This is a type of mutualistic symbiosis, where both organisms benefit from the relationship.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>29","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"At the end of photosynthesis, the green leaf is tested for starch and not glucose, because","images":[],"options":{"A":"the glucose is used up immediately to provide energy for the needs of the leaf","B":"the glucose formed is immediately converted to starch","C":"starch is stored only in leaves","D":"there are no chemicals for glucose test in leaves"},"answer":"B","explanation":"During photosynthesis, plants convert carbon dioxide and water into glucose. This glucose is then immediately converted into starch for storage. Starch is a polysaccharide, a large molecule made up of many glucose units. It is more efficient for plants to store glucose in the form of starch because it is less reactive and takes up less space due to its structure. Therefore, at the end of photosynthesis, the leaf is tested for starch and not glucose because the glucose formed is immediately converted to starch.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>30","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"Which of the following equations is not associated with photosynthesis?","images":[],"options":{"A":"H2O \u2192 H + OH","B":"C6H12O6 \u2192 2C2H5OH + 2CO2","C":"CO2 + [4H] \u2192 CH2O + H2O","D":"4[OH] \u2192 2H2O + O2"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Photosynthesis is the process by which green plants and some other organisms use sunlight to synthesize foods with the aid of chlorophyll pigments. The general equation for photosynthesis is 6CO2 + 6H2O \u2192 C6H12O6 + 6O2. This means that carbon dioxide and water, in the presence of light energy, are converted to glucose and oxygen. The second option, C6H12O6 \u2192 2C2H5OH + 2CO2, is the equation for the fermentation of glucose into ethanol and carbon dioxide, not photosynthesis.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>31","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : NUTRIENT CYCLING IN NATURE","question":"Which of these processes removes carbon from the atmosphere?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Putrefaction of animals","B":"Burning of fuels","C":"Photosynthesis","D":"Volcanic eruption"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Photosynthesis is the process by which green plants and some other organisms use sunlight to synthesize foods with the help of chlorophyll pigments. During photosynthesis, plants absorb carbon dioxide (CO2) from the atmosphere and use it to produce glucose (C6H12O6), which is a type of sugar. This process effectively removes carbon from the atmosphere, thus helping to reduce the overall concentration of atmospheric CO2. The other options such as putrefaction of animals, burning of fuels, and volcanic eruption all contribute to the release of carbon into the atmosphere, not its removal.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>32","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"Which of the following conditions is not necessary for photosynthesis to occur in plants?","images":[],"options":{"A":"There must be light","B":"There must be xylem tissue used to conduct water","C":"There must be chlorophyll to trap radiant energy","D":"Carbondioxide must be present"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Photosynthesis is the process by which green plants and some other organisms use sunlight to synthesize foods with the aid of chlorophyll pigments. The necessary conditions for photosynthesis to occur include light, chlorophyll, and carbon dioxide. However, the presence of xylem tissue is not a direct requirement for photosynthesis. Xylem tissue is involved in the transport of water from the roots to other parts of the plant, but it is not a condition for photosynthesis to occur. Therefore, the statement 'There must be xylem tissue used to conduct water' is not a necessary condition for photosynthesis.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>33","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"The distribution of organisms in a fresh - water habitat like a stream or pond is determined by the following except","images":[],"options":{"A":"rainfall","B":"temperature","C":"pH of soil","D":"light penetration"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The distribution of organisms in a fresh-water habitat like a stream or pond is determined by several factors such as temperature, light penetration, and rainfall. These factors directly affect the living conditions of the organisms. For instance, temperature affects the metabolic rates of organisms, light penetration affects photosynthetic organisms, and rainfall can affect the water level and flow rate. However, the pH of soil is not a direct factor in determining the distribution of organisms in a fresh-water habitat. The pH of the water itself could be a factor, but not the pH of the soil. Therefore, the correct answer is 'pH of soil'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>34","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : HABITATS","question":"Which of the following is characteristics of a swamp?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Vegetation with stratified arrangement","B":"mesophytes with broad leaves","C":"The ground is flooded most of the time","D":"Predominance of climbing plants"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A swamp is a wetland that is forested, meaning it is covered with water for most of the time. Therefore, the characteristic of a swamp is that the ground is flooded most of the time. The other options do not accurately describe a swamp. Stratified arrangement of vegetation is more characteristic of a rainforest, mesophytes with broad leaves are plants that live in an environment with a moderate amount of water, and predominance of climbing plants is more characteristic of a tropical rainforest.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>35","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : HABITATS","question":"Very low annual rainfall, sparse vegetation, high day temperatures and cold nights are the characteristic of the biome known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"swamp","B":"tropical forest","C":"southern guinea savanna","D":"desert"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The characteristics described in the question are typical of a desert biome. Deserts are known for their very low annual rainfall, sparse vegetation due to the lack of water, and extreme temperature fluctuations between day and night. During the day, the temperatures can be extremely high due to the direct exposure to the sun's rays, while at night, the temperatures can drop significantly due to the lack of humidity and cloud cover to trap the heat.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>36","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"The graphs below show the results of experiments which investigated the effect of temperature and oxygen on the rate of uptake of certain ions labelled X and Y by a plant root. Use them to answer the question       Which of the following conclusions cannot be drawn from the graphs?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"Ion is taken up more rapidly at suitable temperature","B":"Suitable oxygen concentration increases ion uptake","C":"Ion uptake requires energy from aerobic respiration of sugar","D":"The quantity of ions absorbed is inversely proportional to the quantity of carbohydrate (sugar) synthesized."},"answer":"D","explanation":"While the right graph shows a decrease in sugar levels as ion uptake increases with oxygen concentration, it does not explicitly demonstrate a direct inverse proportionality between ion absorption and carbohydrate synthesis. The relationship might suggest a trend, but the graphs do not provide enough evidence to conclude an exact inverse proportional relationship.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>37","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"The graphs below show the results of experiments which investigated the effect of temperature and oxygen on the rate of uptake of certain ions labelled X and Y by a plant root. Use them to answer the question     Which of the temperature ranges will likely favour the plant best?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"0 -10oC","B":"15 -20oC","C":"30 -40oC","D":"45 -50oC"},"answer":"C","explanation":"30o -40oC. Both ions X and Y show their maximum uptake within the temperature range of 30o to 40oC  . This indicates that the plant's ion uptake mechanisms operate most efficiently within this range, making it the most favorable temperature range for the plant's ion absorption.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>38","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : FOOD WEBS AND TROPHIC LEVELS","question":"Which of the following is the correct chain for the organism found in an aquatic community?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Paramecium, Phytoplankton, Prawn, Waterflea, Tilapia, Shark","B":"Waterflea, Paramecium, Phytoplankton, Prawn, Tilapia, Shark","C":"Phytoplankton, Waterflea, Paramecium, Prawn, Shark, `tilapia","D":"Phytoplankton, Paramecium, Waterflea, Prawn, Tilapia, Shark"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In an aquatic community, the food chain typically starts with Phytoplankton, which are primary producers. They are eaten by Paramecium (a type of zooplankton), which in turn are eaten by Waterfleas. Waterfleas are then consumed by Prawns, which are eaten by Tilapia (a type of fish). Finally, Sharks, being apex predators, eat Tilapia. Therefore, the correct chain is Phytoplankton, Paramecium, Waterflea, Prawn, Tilapia, Shark.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>39","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : FOOD WEBS AND TROPHIC LEVELS","question":"In a food chain the position occupied by an organism is called","images":[],"options":{"A":"the trophic level","B":"energy level","C":"the feeding level","D":"the habitat level"},"answer":"A","explanation":"In a food chain, the position occupied by an organism is called the trophic level. A trophic level of an organism is the position it occupies in a food chain. The primary producers (plants) occupy the first trophic level, primary consumers (herbivores) occupy the second trophic level, secondary consumers (carnivores) occupy the third trophic level, and so on. The other options do not accurately describe the position of an organism in a food chain.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>40","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : FOOD WEBS AND TROPHIC LEVELS","question":"Which of these statements about food chain is not correct?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Animals in the chain are consumers","B":"A food chain usually begins with a green plant","C":"All organisms in a food chain are animals","D":"Living things are dependent on one another"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A food chain represents the flow of energy and nutrients in an ecosystem, starting from producers (usually green plants) and moving up to different levels of consumers (animals). The statement 'All organisms in a food chain are animals' is incorrect because a food chain starts with plants (producers) which are not animals. They use sunlight to produce food through a process called photosynthesis. Herbivores (plant-eating animals) then eat these plants, and carnivores (meat-eating animals) eat the herbivores. Hence, a food chain includes both plants and animals.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>41","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : NUTRIENT CYCLING IN NATURE","question":"Which of these is not applicable to the circulation of water in nature?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Water removed from oceans are Permanently lost","B":"Water constantly evaporates from the seas, rivers, lakes and soil","C":"Water vapour rises, cools, condenses and precipitates as rain and dew","D":"Water is absorbed by plants and animals from their external environment"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The statement 'Water removed from oceans are Permanently lost' is not applicable to the circulation of water in nature. This is because the water cycle, also known as the hydrologic cycle, is a continuous process where water evaporates, travels into the air and becomes part of a cloud, falls down to earth as precipitation, and then evaporates again. This cycle is a closed system, meaning no water is permanently lost from the oceans. The other options correctly describe processes involved in the water cycle.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>42","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGICAL MANAGEMENT : BIOLOGICAL ASSOCIATIONS","question":"An association between two organisms in which both benefit is called","images":[],"options":{"A":"parasitism","B":"commensalism","C":"symbiosis","D":"Predation"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The association between two organisms in which both benefit is called symbiosis. In biology, symbiosis refers to a close, long-term interaction between two different species. In a symbiotic relationship, both organisms benefit from the association. Parasitism is a non-mutual relationship between species, where one species, the parasite, benefits at the expense of the other, the host. Commensalism is a relationship between two organisms where one organism benefits without affecting the other. Predation is a biological interaction where a predator (an organism that is hunting) feeds on its prey (the organism that is attacked).","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>43","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGY OF POPULATION : ECOLOGICAL SUCCESSION","question":"Which of the following is not an outcome of ecological succession?","images":[],"options":{"A":"There is a progressive change in species structure, organic matter and energy flow","B":"The climax stage consists of a comparatively long lasting species composition","C":"There is no dynamic equilibrium between the community and habitat in the climax stage","D":"Communities occurring later in the sequence of succession are more complex"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Ecological succession is the process of change in the species structure of an ecological community over time. The climax stage in ecological succession is characterized by a stable community which has reached a steady state, or dynamic equilibrium, with the environment. This means that there is indeed a dynamic equilibrium between the community and habitat in the climax stage","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>44","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGY OF POPULATION : FACTORS THAT AFFECT POPULATION","question":"Which of the following is not an effect of over-crowding on a population?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Death","B":"Competition","C":"Commensalism","D":"Aggression"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Overcrowding in a population often leads to increased death rates, competition for resources, and aggression among individuals. However, commensalism, which is a type of symbiotic relationship where one organism benefits while the other is neither harmed nor benefited, is not a direct effect of overcrowding. Overcrowding does not necessarily lead to commensalism as this relationship depends more on the specific interactions between different species rather than the density of a population.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>45","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HEALTH : MICROORGANISMS IN ACTION","question":"The diagram above represent the shape of major group of bacteria  The groups staphylococci and streptobacilli are represented by","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"I and II","B":"II and IV","C":"III and VII","D":"IV and VII"},"answer":"D","explanation":"IV (Staphylococci): This group is characterized by the grape-like clusters of spherical bacteria, typical of the staphylococci arrangement.  VII (Streptobacilli): This group is characterized by the chain-like arrangement of rod-shaped bacteria, typical of streptobacilli.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>46","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : SOIL, WATER, WILDLIFE, FOREST AND MINERALS","question":"Prevention of erosion could best be carried out by","images":[],"options":{"A":"crop rotation and mulching","B":"contouring of slopping ground and afforestation","C":"grazing, terracing and shifting cultivation","D":"strip cropping and poaching"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Erosion is the process of wearing away of the land surface by physical forces such as rainfall, flowing water, wind, ice, temperature change, gravity or other natural or anthropogenic agents. It can be prevented by various methods. Among the given options, contouring of sloping ground and afforestation is the best method to prevent erosion. Contouring of sloping ground involves plowing across a slope following its elevation contour lines. These contour lines create a water break which reduces the formation of rills and gullies during times of heavy water run-off; which is a major cause of top soil loss and soil erosion. Afforestation is the establishment of a forest, or stand of trees, in an area where there was no forest. This is often done to prevent erosion as trees prevent erosion by binding the soil with their roots. The other options like crop rotation and mulching, grazing terracing and shifting cultivation, strip cropping and poaching also help in preventing erosion but not as effectively as contouring and afforestation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>47","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : WAYS OF ENSURING CONSERVATION","question":"The following are useful measures for conserving forest except","images":[],"options":{"A":"preventing and controlling accidental forest fire","B":"encouraging the use of charcoal for industrial and domestic purposes","C":"combating and preventing plant diseases","D":"reafforestation of depleted forest"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct answer is 'encouraging the use of charcoal for industrial and domestic purposes'. This is because the production of charcoal involves cutting down trees and burning them, which contributes to deforestation. Deforestation is the opposite of forest conservation. The other options involve measures that help to protect and restore forests. Preventing and controlling accidental forest fires helps to prevent the destruction of forests. Combating and preventing plant diseases helps to keep the trees in the forest healthy. Reafforestation of depleted forest involves planting new trees in areas where the forest has been cut down, which helps to restore the forest.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>48","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : SOIL, WATER, WILDLIFE, FOREST AND MINERALS","question":"The following practices are aimed at soil conservation except","images":[],"options":{"A":"contour ridging","B":"application of manures","C":"strip cropping","D":"bush clearing"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Soil conservation involves practices that are aimed at preventing soil erosion or degradation. Contour ridging, application of manures, and strip cropping are all practices that help in soil conservation. Contour ridging helps in reducing the speed of water flow, thus reducing soil erosion. Application of manures improves the soil structure and its capacity to hold water, thus reducing soil erosion. Strip cropping involves growing crops in a systematic way in rows or strips which helps in reducing soil erosion. On the other hand, bush clearing, which involves removing vegetation cover, can lead to soil erosion as it exposes the soil to wind and water. Therefore, bush clearing is not aimed at soil conservation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>49","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL COMPONENTS","question":"Which of the following natural resources is most readily available to all organisms?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Water","B":"Oil","C":"Food","D":"Air"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The most readily available natural resource to all organisms is air. All organisms, regardless of their habitat, require air to survive. Air is composed of various gases such as oxygen, which is essential for respiration in animals, and carbon dioxide, which is necessary for photosynthesis in plants. Water, food, and oil are also natural resources, but their availability varies greatly depending on the organism and its habitat. For example, desert organisms have adapted to survive with very little water, and not all organisms require oil or the same type of food. Therefore, air is the most universally available resource to all organisms.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>50","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"VARIATION IN POPULATION : MORPHOLOGICAL VARIATIONS","question":"Which of the following is an example of discontinuous variation?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Height","B":"Size of head","C":"Blood group","D":"Skin colour"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Discontinuous variation refers to the variation in characteristics that have a definite form. These characteristics are controlled by a single pair of genes. Examples of discontinuous variation include blood group, ability to roll the tongue, etc. In this case, the blood group is an example of discontinuous variation because there are distinct categories (A, B, AB, O) and no intermediates.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>51","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"Hereditary variation is best described as","images":[],"options":{"A":"characters transmitted from generation to generation","B":"traits acquired from diseases","C":"characters that show up due to social conditions","D":"traits acquired from habits and environmental conditions"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Hereditary variation refers to the differences that exist within species that are passed down through successive generations. These variations are caused by genetic differences, which are transmitted from parents to offspring. Therefore, the best description of hereditary variation is 'characters transmitted from generation to generation'. The other options refer to acquired traits, which are not hereditary in nature.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>52","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : TRANSMISSION AND EXPRESSION OF CHARACTERISTICS IN ORGANISMS","question":"An individual with blood group AB can receive blood from those in blood group(s)","images":[],"options":{"A":"AB only B","B":"A and B only","C":"B only","D":"A, B, AB and O"},"answer":"D","explanation":"An individual with blood group AB is considered a universal recipient. This is because they have both A and B antigens on their red blood cells, and therefore, their immune system will not produce antibodies against either A or B blood types. As a result, they can receive blood from donors of any blood group: A, B, AB, or O.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>53","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"The statement that the environment determines which organisms survives to reproduce","images":[],"options":{"A":"explains the theory of acquired characters","B":"supports Jean Lamarck's theory of use and disuse","C":"supports the idea of survival of the fittest","D":"is refuted by fossil records"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The statement that the environment determines which organisms survive to reproduce supports the idea of survival of the fittest. This concept is a key component of the theory of natural selection, proposed by Charles Darwin. According to this theory, individuals that are better adapted to their environment are more likely to survive and reproduce, thereby passing on their advantageous traits to the next generation. This process leads to changes in the species over time, a process known as evolution.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>54","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"Which of the following is a definition of heredity? It is the","images":[],"options":{"A":"non-resemblance of closely related organisms","B":"total absence of parental traits in offspring","C":"absence of variation in organisms","D":"transfer of characteristics from parents to offspring"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Heredity is the transfer of characteristics from parents to offspring. This is a fundamental concept in genetics, the study of how traits are passed from one generation to the next. Traits can include physical characteristics like eye color or hair type, or more complex traits like susceptibility to certain diseases. The other options do not accurately define heredity. Non-resemblance of closely related organisms, total absence of parental traits in offspring, and absence of variation in organisms are not definitions of heredity.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>55","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : CHROMOSOMES","question":"Which of the following is not a reason why an offspring looks different from its parents?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Random reorganisation of chromosome during gamete formation","B":"Existence of multiple alleles in organisms","C":"Formation of chasmata in chromatids during meiosis","D":"Mitosis of the zygote produces new combination of chromosomes"},"answer":"D","explanation":"An offspring looks different from its parents due to genetic variation, which can be caused by several factors such as random reorganisation of chromosomes during gamete formation, existence of multiple alleles in organisms, and formation of chasmata in chromatids during meiosis. However, mitosis of the zygote does not produce new combinations of chromosomes. Instead, it results in identical cells with the same genetic information as the parent cell. Therefore, mitosis of the zygote is not a reason why an offspring looks different from its parents.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>56","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"The pair of genes expressed in a heterozygous individual is described as","images":[],"options":{"A":"allele","B":"chromatid","C":"dominant gene","D":"centrosome"},"answer":"A","explanation":"In genetics, an allele refers to one of two or more versions of a gene that are found at the same place on a chromosome. In a heterozygous individual, two different alleles of a gene are present. Therefore, the pair of genes expressed in a heterozygous individual is described as an allele. A chromatid is one half of a duplicated chromosome, a dominant gene is an allele that is fully expressed in the phenotype of a heterozygote, and a centrosome is an organelle that serves as the main microtubule organizing center of the animal cell as well as a regulator of cell-cycle progression.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>57","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"The following structures are adaptation for water conservation except","images":[],"options":{"A":"sunken stomata","B":"scales in animals","C":"lenticels in stems","D":"spines in plants"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Adaptations for water conservation in organisms include features that reduce water loss. Sunken stomata, scales in animals, and spines in plants are all adaptations that help to conserve water. Sunken stomata are a feature of many desert plants that help to reduce water loss during transpiration. Scales in animals, particularly reptiles, help to prevent water loss from the body surface. Spines in plants, which are modified leaves, reduce the surface area for water loss. However, lenticels in stems are not an adaptation for water conservation. Lenticels are small pores in the bark of stems and roots of woody plants that allow for gas exchange between the atmosphere and the internal tissues. They do not play a role in water conservation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>58","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"Which of the following ecological factors causes food shortage?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Low rate of reproduction","B":"Emigration","C":"Drought","D":"Topography"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Drought is an ecological factor that can cause food shortage. Drought conditions can lead to a lack of water, which is essential for the growth of plants. Plants form the base of the food chain, and a decrease in plant growth can lead to a decrease in the availability of food for herbivores. This can then affect the entire food chain, leading to a food shortage. Low rate of reproduction, emigration, and topography can affect the availability of food, but they do not directly cause food shortage.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>59","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : POPULATION STUDIES BY SAMPLING","question":"Density, mortality rate, birth rate are the factors that affect","images":[],"options":{"A":"population","B":"dominance","C":"cover","D":"habitat"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Density, mortality rate, and birth rate are all factors that directly influence the size and growth of a population. Density refers to the number of individuals per unit area or volume. Mortality rate is the number of deaths in a population over a certain period of time, while birth rate is the number of live births over the same period. These factors together determine the size of the population and its growth rate. Therefore, the correct answer is 'population'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1995>60","subject":"Biology","year":"1995","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS","question":"Ultra-filtration process at the Bowman's capsule is facilitated by","images":[],"options":{"A":"the volume of water in the blood","B":"the high concentration of urea in the blood of the Bowman's capsule","C":"the differential blood pressure between the glomerulus and the Bowman's capsule","D":"the differential blood volume between the glomerulus and the Bowman's capsule"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Ultra-filtration in the Bowman's capsule is facilitated by the differential blood pressure between the glomerulus and the Bowman's capsule. This process involves the filtration of blood under high pressure in the glomerulus, leading to the formation of glomerular filtrate in the Bowman's capsule. The high pressure is due to the difference in the diameter of the afferent and efferent arterioles. The afferent arteriole that brings blood to the glomerulus is wider than the efferent arteriole that carries blood away from the glomerulus. This creates a pressure gradient which aids in the filtration process.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"}];